    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 264582,
      "reputation" : 83228,
      "user_id" : 550966,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 97,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/mR97lFDs.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Pankaj Kumar",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/550966/pankaj-kumar"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 435,
    "last_activity_date" : 1538836369,
    "last_edit_date" : 1538836369,
    "creation_date" : 1399032620,
    "answer_id" : 23427862,
    "question_id" : 16931327,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<blockquote>\n  <p>WAY-1 : Updated for the shortest and easy way</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Below command will give you the path, <em>But it will only work if java command is working in other words if java path is configured</em>. </p>\n\n<pre><code>readlink -f $(which java) \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Read more at <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5251323/where-can-i-find-the-java-sdk-in-linux\">Where can I find the Java SDK in Linux?</a></p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>WAY-2 (Better than WAY-1) : Below answer is still working and try it if above command is not working\n  for you. </p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>You need to dig into symbolic links. Below is steps to get Java directory</p>\n\n<p>Step 1:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ whereis java\njava: /usr/bin/java /etc/java /usr/share/java\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>That tells the command java resides in /usr/bin/java.</p>\n\n<p>Dig again:</p>\n\n<p>Step 2:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ ls -l /usr/bin/java\nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 22 2009-01-15 18:34 /usr/bin/java -&gt; /etc/alternatives/java\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>So, now we know that <code>/usr/bin/java</code> is actually a symbolic link to <code>/etc/alternatives/java</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Dig deeper using the same method above:</p>\n\n<p>Step 3:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ ls -l /etc/alternatives/java\nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 31 2009-01-15 18:34 /etc/alternatives/java -&gt; /usr/local/jre1.6.0_07/bin/java\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>So, thats the actual location of java: <code>/usr/local/jre.....</code></p>\n\n<p>You could still dig deeper to find other symbolic links.</p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Reference : <a href=\"http://ubuntuforums.org/showthread.php?t=1054731\" rel=\"noreferrer\">where is java's home dir?</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2513477,
